#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:3
msgid "Compatibility with rustdoc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:5
msgid ""
"This document compares the rustdoc markdown syntax and features with those "
"supported by this extension via myst-parser. It also provides an explanation "
"of the various myst-parser extensions that enable this compatibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:10
msgid "Markdown syntax"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:12
msgid ""
"myst-parser and `Rust's markdown`_ both target the CommonMark specification. "
"However, Rust provides some `additional features`_ that are not part of the "
"CommonMark specification. Almost all of these syntax extensions are "
"supported by myst-parser. The :ref:`Markdown usage <md usage>` sections "
"lists all the extensions required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:16
msgid ""
"To make the docstrings work with both rustdoc and this tool, the following "
"changes may be required to existing docstrings:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:19
msgid "Use double tilde (``~~``) only for strike-through."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:20
msgid ""
"Use a backslash in front of literal text enclosed in brackets (``\\[foo]`` "
"instead of ``[foo]``) to prevent it from being rendered as broken link."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:22
msgid ""
"Replace links that use ``Self::``, ``self::`` or ``super::`` with the name "
"of the type, value or macro. Links with ``crate::`` in the target do not "
"need to be updated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:24
msgid ""
"Use explicit text for the hyperlink when using namespaces and "
"disambiguators, as in ``[`Foo`](struct@Foo)`` instead of ``[`struct@Foo`]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:27
msgid ""
"The sections below cover any differences in syntax and extensions required "
"to make docstrings work with both Rust and Sphinx."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:31
msgid "Attrs block"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:33
msgid ""
"The ``attrs_block`` extension is used to separate the sections within "
"docstrings from the sections of the table of contents. Essentially, the "
"markdown sections in the docstrings are handled separately from the sections "
"of the page. See the warning in https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/"
"syntax/organising_content.html#document-structure for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:39
msgid "Colon-fencing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:41
msgid ""
"The ``colon_fence`` extensions allows using colons (``:::``) for fencing "
"instead of the usual back-ticks. This is used when generating the docs so "
"they can be rendered properly in other markdown compatible tools. Removing "
"this extension will cause issues with the generated documentation. See "
"https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/syntax/optional.html#code-"
"fences-using-colons for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:47
msgid "Strikethrough"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:49
msgid ""
"Enable the ``strikethrough`` extension for myst-parser in ``conf.py`` and "
"use ``~~`` for strikethrough in the docstrings. Rust supports a single "
"``~``, but myst-parser does not. See https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/"
"latest/syntax/optional.html#strikethrough for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:54
msgid "Footnotes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:56
msgid ""
"Both Rust and myst-parser use the same syntax for footnotes, so they should "
"work as is. See https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/syntax/"
"typography.html#footnotes for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:60
msgid "Tables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:62
msgid ""
"Both Rust and myst-parser target the `GitHub markdown table syntax`_. It "
"should work out of the box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:65
msgid "Tasks List"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:67
msgid ""
"Enable the ``tasklist`` extension for myst-parser in ``conf.py``. The syntax "
"is the same with this extension enabled. See https://myst-parser.readthedocs."
"io/en/latest/syntax/optional.html#task-lists for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:71
msgid "Smart punctuation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:73
msgid ""
"Enable the ``smartquotes`` and ``replacements`` extensions for myst-parser "
"in ``conf.py``. This will enable smart punctuation similar to Rust's "
"markdown and some more. See https://myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/"
"syntax/optional.html#typography for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:78
msgid "Warning blocks and admonitions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:80
msgid ""
"Rust uses a separate div class for this as described `here <https://doc.rust-"
"lang.org/rustdoc/how-to-write-documentation.html#adding-a-warning-block>`_. "
"To support a similar syntax for admonitions, enable the ``html_admonition`` "
"extension for myst-parser in ``conf.py``. See https://myst-parser."
"readthedocs.io/en/latest/syntax/optional.html#html-admonitions for details. "
"There are some additional features supported by myst-parser compared to Rust."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:86
msgid ""
"myst-parser supports Sphinx admonition directives as described at https://"
"myst-parser.readthedocs.io/en/latest/syntax/admonitions.html, but they will "
"not be rendered by rustdoc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:90
msgid "rustdoc features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:93
msgid "Missing docs warning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:95
msgid ""
"This extension does not check for missing documentation when executed. It "
"will list any items that it discovers, even when there are no docs for them. "
"The warning may be supported in future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:99
msgid "#[doc] attributes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:101
msgid ""
"`Crate level doc attributes`_ are not supported. Most crate level doc "
"attributes deal with the publication of the HTML and executing doctests. If "
"any of these attributes are present, they are ignored when extracting the "
"docs. The behavior of some HTML attributes may be achieved via Sphinx "
"configuration options and extensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:105
msgid ""
"`Item level doc attributes`_ are not supported at present, but future "
"versions may support some of them. This section will be updated as support "
"for various attributes is implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:109
msgid "Re-exports"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:111
msgid ""
"`Re-exports`_ are supported similar to rustdoc, with some differences in "
"behavior. The tool does not currently recognize rustdoc attributes like "
"``inline``, ``hidden`` and ``noinline``. So, inlining is done purely based "
"on whether the item will be documented in its original location or in a re-"
"exported location. Documentation for the re-export is combined with the "
"documentation of the original item, if the item is inlined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:119
msgid "Intra-doc links"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:121
msgid ""
"`Intra-doc links`_ are supported using all 4 syntax shown in the examples "
"for Markdown only. However, using ``Self::``, ``self::`` and ``super::`` in "
"the link target is not supported. Link targets with ``crate::`` are "
"supported. (See Valid links section below.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:125
msgid ""
"Currently, it is necessary to add a backslash (``\\``) in front of a literal "
"text that appears within brackets (``\\[foo]`` instead of ``[foo]``). "
"Otherwise, there will be a warning regarding unresolved references and the "
"text will be rendered as a broken link. The backslash will remove this issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:129
msgid ""
"For reStructuredText, it is recommended to use the :rst:role:`rust:any` role "
"as the default Sphinx role for references to support similar behavior. With "
"that added to Sphinx configuration, references can simply be written as "
"```ref```, without specifying the type of the reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:134
msgid "Valid links"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:136
msgid ""
"Rustdoc provides a rich syntax for `valid links`_. However, this tool does "
"not support any of those features, except link references beginning with "
"``crate::`` and references to items with generic parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:139
msgid ""
"Additionally, the tool cannot link to items outside of the crate(s) being "
"documented, including the standard library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:143
msgid "Namespaces and disambiguators"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:145
msgid ""
"`Namespaces and disambiguators`_ are supported by this tool and will resolve "
"correctly, but the prefixes are not stripped. To remove prefixes, use an "
"explicit text for the link. ``[`Foo`](struct@Foo)`` will render as ``Foo``, "
"but ``[`struct@Foo`]`` will render as ``[struct@Foo]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:150
msgid "Lints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../docs/compatibility.rst:152
msgid ""
"The `rustdoc-specific lints`_ are not supported currently. There are no "
"plans to support them at present. If this is required, please create an "
"issue."
msgstr ""
